references: We now present experimental details and results for evaluating dataset similarity using our metric. We also compare our metric to the original Wasserstein distance with a Euclidean cost function. To test our dataset-agnostic claim, we include a variety of data types and tasks typically used in FL (Table 1, Section D.1 for full details). For each dataset, we asses the performance of five different training algorithms: (1) Single site training (each site trains a separate model) which serves as our baseline. (2) Joint training where one model is trained on the combined datasets. (3) FL using FedAvg (McMahan etÂ al., 2017). (4) FL using Personalized Federated Learning with Moreau Envelopes, i.e., pFedME (TÂ Dinh etÂ al., 2020). (5) FL using Ditto (Li etÂ al., 2021). pFedME and Ditto are two popular personalized FL algorithms. The code for data partitioning, calculation of dataset similarity, and model training can be found at github.com/annoymous-submissions/ot_cost.
